## Step 1: Building It

Before you can use a function, you must build (define) it. We use the keyword **`function`** followed by a name, parentheses `()`, and curly braces `{}`.

```javascript
function sayHello() {
  console.log("Hello there!");
  console.log("Have a great day!");
}
```

**Note:** When you write this code, nothing actually prints to the console! Why? Because we only *built* the machine. We haven't turned it on yet!

## Step 2: Turning It On

To make the function run, we have to **"Call"** or **"Invoke"** it. 

We do this simply by writing the function's name followed by parentheses `()`.

```javascript
sayHello(); // The machine runs! Prints both lines.

// We can run it 100 times if we want!
sayHello(); 
sayHello();
```

The parentheses are the "ON" button! Without them, JavaScript just stares at the machine and does nothing.

